    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-08-31T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-08-31T00:00:00-05:00" n="655"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d655">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.20/134</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Assistant Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Berle</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Under Secretary of State</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Welles</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-08-31">August 31,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Welles</hi>: The Committee for a Jewish Army has been
                    besieging the White House. McIntyre<note n="17" xml:id="d655fn17">Marvin H.
                        McIntyre, Secretary to President Roosevelt.</note> eventually sent them to
                    me. They were then thinking of a huge delegation to convince the British that
                        <pb facs="0557" n="545" xml:id="pg_545"/> the Jewish Army ought to go
                    forward. They have finally got their suggestions to a point where they wish to
                    send four people, namely: <list>
                        <item>Alfred A. Strelsin of New York;</item>
                        <item>Kenneth Leslie of the “Protestant Digest”;</item>
                        <item>Andrew L. Somers, a Member of Congress, and</item>
                        <item>Peter H. Bergson, a Palestinian expert,</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">on private passports to England to lay their cases before the
                    British authorities. The chairman of the committee, Strelsin, has been talking
                    at length to Field Marshal Sir John Dill,<note n="18" xml:id="d655fn18">Ranking
                        British officer on the Combined Chiefs of Staff.</note> and this is the
                    procedure finally recommended by him.</p>
                <p>I see no reason why we should not grant passports with reasonable priority; but
                    the understanding is that they are merely going to state the case as well as
                    they can to the appropriate British authority and try to persuade the British to
                    make up their minds. This Government does not assume any responsibility for them
                    except as it permits their trip. Do you see any objection?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>A. A. B[<hi rend="smallcaps">erle</hi>], <hi rend="smallcaps">Jr.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
